			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1672">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I opened the October 2005 issue expecting to be transported into someone else&rsquo;s reality. Instead Thea Sullivan&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/299">Trying</a>&rdquo; thrust me right back into my own mourning.</p>

<p>I recently experienced my first (and hopefully last) miscarriage. I, too, have listened to well-meaning individuals refer to this death as &ldquo;God&rsquo;s will,&rdquo; while others have tiptoed around the topic, unsure of how to approach it, or me. I pretend I&rsquo;m fine, but I can&rsquo;t help feeling enraged, because I did everything &ldquo;right&rdquo;: I am married. I am thirty-one. I have a good job. I own a home. I don&rsquo;t smoke or drink or do drugs. I <em>wanted </em>this baby.</p>

<p>I am somewhat consoled by those who say, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry this happened to you.&rdquo; I only want my loss to be validated. To Sullivan, and to all women who have suffered similar losses, I say: I&rsquo;m sorry this happened to you.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Anne Fearman<br>Forestville, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1648">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I&rsquo;ve always had a smug tendency to dismiss infertility as trivial in comparison to other medical problems. Thea Sullivan&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/299">Trying</a>&rdquo; [October 2005] brought the profound suffering of infertile couples into sharp focus and aroused my compassion.</p>

<p>As a father of three I can&rsquo;t know the pain of Sullivan&rsquo;s situation, but I am familiar with the metaphysical questions she raised in her essay. I, too, have found out the hard way that spiritual fads (as well as ancient traditions) offer only partial or dangerously naive answers to our suffering. Following the lead of various popular books, I spent many years trying to unravel the meaning of seemingly symbolic events and encounters in my daily life. I trusted ethereal &ldquo;soul guides,&rdquo; who spoke the language of synchronicity, to lead me to healing, great relationships, and self-actualization. I found my expectations dashed time and again.</p>

<p>Like Sullivan, I&rsquo;ve since assumed a more contemplative stance and made peace with mystery. Cryptic &ldquo;messages&rdquo; continue to arrive with almost ridiculous frequency, whether I look for them or not, but I accept that their meaning is beyond my comprehension &mdash; probably due to my unconscious tendency to interpret them in the context of my own short-sighted needs and desires. Either the intelligence behind such messages is dedicated to driving me mad, or it is simply saying hello and letting me know it hasn&rsquo;t given up on me &mdash; hopefully the latter.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Johnson<br>Guilford, Connecticut</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1649">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was moved by Thea Sullivan&rsquo;s beautiful, lucid prose and the pain she and her husband experienced during their struggle with infertility. I was saddened, however, that they chose to pursue fertility treatment rather than adoption. In addition to the health risks that Sullivan mentions, there are ethical and ecological reasons to oppose such treatments. Thousands of nonhuman animals &mdash; particularly female monkeys &mdash; are used in fertility, menstruation, and reproduction studies each year. These studies are inherently cruel to the animals involved and result in their suffering and death.</p>

<p>With 6.5 billion humans on the planet and species becoming extinct at an unprecedented rate, there is no environmental benefit from artificially induced human fertility. Adoption, on the other hand, benefits everyone. There are plenty of kids in this world who need a home.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jennifer Campbell<br>Cambridge, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1650">
								<p><a href="/contributors/thea-sullivan"><strong>Thea Sullivan</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>Jennifer Campbell seems to suggest that infertile couples bear more responsibility than others for the ecological and ethical crises that we, as a society, face. Animal studies are conducted to develop treatments for a wide range of medical conditions, and despite their cruelty, we all benefit from them at some point. And shouldn&rsquo;t everyone &mdash; fertile or not &mdash; bear equal responsibility for overpopulating the planet? (It goes without saying that children born of fertility treatments constitute a tiny portion of the world&rsquo;s population.)</p>

<p>Though it&rsquo;s inarguable that many children need homes, the implication that everyone facing infertility should adopt is naive and runs counter to conventional wisdom about adoption. Some couples who can&rsquo;t conceive are quickly drawn to adoption, while others discover within themselves a surprisingly deep longing to become biological parents. Adoption professionals encourage such couples to pursue any fertility treatments they deem necessary before beginning an adoption search, since unacknowledged ambivalence can impair a new parent&rsquo;s attachment to an adopted child and cause that child further wounding.</p>

<p>When you&rsquo;ve traveled the often harrowing path of infertility, you learn how painful it is to be judged for what are ultimately deeply personal choices. That&rsquo;s why, within infertility circles, there is a compassionate acceptance for the different ways families are created, and for the decision to remain without children. In her effort to correct society&rsquo;s injustices, Campbell seems to be forgetting to practice this sort of compassion.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

